# Git Commit & Push Hygiene

## After a rebase, always force-push with lease

A plain `git push` will fail with non-fast-forward after `git rebase`. Default to:

```bash
git push --force-with-lease origin HEAD
```

Never use plain `--force` (clobbers upstream changes from collaborators). Never use plain `git push` expecting it to work after a rebase.

If the user says "update the PR" or "push" after any of the following, use `--force-with-lease`:
- `git rebase`
- `git commit --amend`
- `git reset` that moved HEAD backwards
- Any interactive history rewrite

## Updating an existing PR after a rebase

When the user asks to "update the PR" on a rebased branch:

1. Sanity-check the history: `git log --oneline origin/main..HEAD` — confirm the expected commits are present, nothing extra, nothing missing.
2. `git push --force-with-lease origin HEAD`
3. Find the PR: `gh pr list --head <branch> --json number,title,url` — report the PR URL back to the user.
4. If review feedback was addressed during the rebase/fix session, consider posting a PR comment summarizing what changed. Use `gh pr comment <number> --body "..."` with a brief bullet list per issue addressed.

## What a good "update the PR" response looks like

```
Pushed force-with-lease to feat/my-feature.

PR: https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>/pull/123
Commits now on the branch (3):
  7e372f81 refactor: ...
  f1232f31 feat: ...
  ...
```

## Never

- Never `git push --force` without `--with-lease`. If `--with-lease` is rejected, stop and show the user what upstream changed — do not blindly override.
- Never force-push to `main` / `master` / `release/*` branches without the user explicitly requesting it.
